<font color="#FF0000">NAM, MY COUNTRY NOT MY HOME</font><br>
<tt>Tue Nov 26 11:02:07 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
   I left Vietnam when I was 3 years old.  Now at 19 and in college, I've learned to live the American way.  <br>
   I do not know much about my country; only what my parents and grandparents had told me.  The sweet memories of the past, a home that they long for but sacrificed in order to come to America to insure a better life for their children.<br>
  Most of my family reside here in the States.  My mom's side of the family are still back in Saigon.  My mom would tell me how much I have going for me.  She only has my dad, my brothers and I.  She had left everything and everyone she had grew up with for me.  She is there at a touch of a phone call to comfort me and yet she really doesn't have anyone.<br>
  For those people who had lived during the war and the period after, please understand the innocent.  We had left our homeland for a chance.  A chance that we deserve just as much as anyone else.  The War is over.  Twenty years had passed and we should try to move on.  It's terribly difficult to forget the past when you were in the damn situation, but political differences will only pollute your hearts.  <br>
To the soliders : you have answered the call from your beloved country and you are true heroes.  You saw the pain in the eyes of the children and you can still see that sadness in the eyes of my Vietnamese parents.<br>
  Please try to understand.     
<p><code>-- nguyenha@pilot.msu.edu  (Ha Nguyen) </code><p>


